where d1 and d2 are biological noise modelled as normally distributed noise with a mean = 1 and a standard deviation
= R1 . D1 and D2 are technical noise modelled as evenly distributed random variables ranging between 0 and R2
[21]. Note that the parameters for noise are arbitrarily chosen and are used solely for demonstration of potential
eÔ¨Äects on correlation measures. Now, I vary K, R1 , and R2 as follows: K = 10, 000, 1, 000 or 100, and [R1 , R2 ] =
[0.01, 10], [0.03, 30] or [0.09, 90]. Figure 4 shows the log2 transformed plot of Xm (10 < Xm < 1, 000) against Ym
and Table 1 shows PC, SC and MI outputs with diÔ¨Äerent combinations of K and [R1 , R2 ]. At low and moderate noise
levels ([R1 , R2 ] = [0.01, 10] and [0.03, 30], respectively), SC was relatively unaÔ¨Äected by the decrease in K (i.e. the
increase of non-linearity). At the high noise level ([R1 , R2 ] = [0.09, 90]), however, SC was strongly aÔ¨Äected by the
decrease in K, but PC was less aÔ¨Äected. At all noise levels, MI was highly sensitive to the value of K. These results
show that the elevated PC, and the low SC and MI, on analysis of the protein-interacting group, are more likely to
be evident at high levels of non-linearity and noise. As the level of noise will not be signiÔ¨Åcantly diÔ¨Äerent between
HPRD and control groups, nonlinearity will probably be higher when the protein-interacting pairs are considered.
