2.7. Performance of asymmetric correlation
Figure 6 shows histograms of the asymmetric correlation coeÔ¨Écient with respect to the lower right quadrant for
HPRD data and the control data used above. The mean values of the coeÔ¨Écients are 1,599 for HPRD data and 1,002
for control data. When speciÔ¨Åcity and sensitivity were examined as for other correlation measures, the asymmetric
coeÔ¨Écient performed better than did PC. When the speciÔ¨Åcity was 0.9, sensitivity was 0.347 (0.305 with PC), and
when the sensitivity was 0.9, speciÔ¨Åcity was 0.290 (0.257 with PC).
However, better performance could be obtained by combining the asymmetric coeÔ¨Écient with other measures.
Figure 7 shows scatter plots for asymmetric coeÔ¨Écients and PC, SC, and MI of all HPRD pairs (blue) and control
pairs (red). As can be seen in the top-right portion of all three scatter plots, the HPRD pairs were very speciÔ¨Åcally
detected when AC was high and the other measure (i.e. PC, SC or MI) was positive. As a result of this observation, I
introduced a measure which combines PC, SC or MI with AC:
RPC,AC = rP + A
RS C,AC = rS + A
R MI,AC = rM + A
where RPC,AC , RS C,AC and R MI,AC are combined measures for PC and AC, SC and AC, and MI and AC, respectively.
P, S, M and A in the equations are values of PC, SC, MI, and AC respectively and r is a constant. Figure 8 shows
speciÔ¨Åcity at 90% sensitivity and sensitivity at 90% speciÔ¨Åcity when r was varied between 0 and 5,000. With PC
and MI, speciÔ¨Åcity was relatively unaÔ¨Äected by r (maximum values = 0.293 and 0.290 for PC and MI, respectively).
However, the sensitivity increased signiÔ¨Åcantly as r increased and attained peaks (0.448 for PC and 0.389 for MI)
when r = 2,400 and 5,000, respectively. On the other hand, both speciÔ¨Åcity and sensitivity improved with SC when r
was increased to some extent, but all improvements were modest (peak speciÔ¨Åcity and sensitivity = 0.378 and 0.313,

